<section xml:id="sec-submodules">
	<title>Submodules</title>
	<definition xml:id="def-submodule">
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be a left <m>R</m>-module. A subgroup <m>N</m> of <m>M</m> is said to be a <term>submodule of <m>R</m></term> or <term><m>R</m>-submodule</term> if <m>N</m> is closed under the <sq>scalar multiplication</sq> of <m>R</m> on <m>M</m>, i.e., for any <m>r\in R</m> and any <m>n\in N</m> we have <m>r\cdot n\in N</m>.
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<convention>
		A submodule <m>N</m> of a module <m>M</m> is denoted by <m>N\leq M</m>.
	</convention>
	<definition xml:id="def-submodule-generated-by-subset">
		<title>(Submodule generated by a subset)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be a left <m>R</m>-module, and let <m>X</m> be a subset of <m>M</m>. The <term><m>R</m>-submodule generated by <m>X</m></term> is
			<me>\langle X\rangle=\left\{\sum_{i=1}^nr_ix_i:x_i\in M,r_i\in R\;\text{and}\;n\in\N\right\}.</me>
			<p>
				If <m>X</m> is a finite set, say <m>X=\{x_1,\ldots,x_n\}</m> then we write the <m>R</m>-module generated by <m>X</m> as
				<me>Rx_1+Rx_2+\cdots+Rx_n</me>
				and we call such an <m>R</m>-module a <term>finitely generated <m>R</m>-module</term>.
			</p>
			<p>
				In particular, if <m>X={x}</m> then the finitely generated <m>R</m>-module is called <term>principal <m>R</m>-module</term> or <term>cyclic <m>R</m>-module</term>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="module-linear-combination">
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be a left <m>R</m>-module. An element <m>m\in M</m> is said to be an <term><m>R</m>-linear combination of <m>x_1,\ldots,x_n\in M</m></term> if <me>m=r\cdot x_1+\cdots+r\cdot x_n.</me>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<example xml:id="trivial-submodule">
		<title>Trivial submodule</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>R</m> be a ring and let <m>M</m> be a left <m>R</m>-module. The trivial subgroup <m>\{0\}\leq M</m> is an <m>R</m>-submodule of <m>M</m>. Also, module <m>M</m> is an <m>R</m>-submodule of itself.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="vector-subspaces-as-submodules">
		<title>(Vector subspaces are submodules)</title>
		<statement>
			If <m>V</m> is an <m>F</m>-vector space then any subspace of <m>V</m> is an <m>F</m>-submodule of <m>V</m>.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="subgroups-as-submodules">
		<title>(Subgroups of abelian groups as submodules)</title>
		<statement>
			Every subgroup of an abelian group is a <m>\Z</m>-submodule, refer to <xref ref="abelian-groups-Z-modules"/>.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="ideals-as-submodules">
		<title>(Ideals as submodules)</title>
		<statement>
			Consider a ring <m>R</m> as a left module over itself via the left multiplication (see <xref ref="module-over-itself"/>). If <m>I</m> is a left ideal of <m>R</m> then <m>I</m> is a left <m>R</m>-module.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="annihilator-of-module">
		<title>(Annihilator of a module)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>M</m> be a left <m>R</m>-module. By <xref ref="ring-hom-and-modules"/> there is a ring homomorphism <m>R\to\End_{\rm Grps}(M)</m>. The kernel of this ring homomorphism is called the <term>annihilator of <m>M</m></term>:
			<me>{\rm Ann}_R(M)=\{r\in R:r\cdot m=0\;\text{for all}\;m\in M\}</me>
			being a two-sided ideal of <m>R</m> is a left <m>R</m>-submodule of <m>R</m>.
			<p>
				Consider <m>\Z/n\Z</m> as a <m>\Z</m>-module. In this case <m>\Ann_{\Z}(\Z/n\Z)=n\Z</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="invariant-subspaces">
		<title>(Invariant subspaces)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a vector space over a field <m>F</m>, i.e., <m>V</m> is an <m>F</m>-mod. Fix a linear transformation <m>T\in\End_F(V)</m>. As in <xref ref="vs-as-FX-module"/> we consider <m>V</m> as an <m>F[X]</m>-mod. We show that submodules of <m>V</m> as an <m>F[X]</m>-mod are precisely <m>T</m>-invariant <m>F</m>-subspaces of a vector space <m>V</m>.
			<p>
				Assume that <m>W</m> is an <m>F[X]</m>-submodule of <m>V</m>. First observe that <m>W</m> is also an <m>F</m>-subspace of <m>V</m>. Indeed, under <m>F[X]</m>-module structure any constant polynomial <m>a\in F[X]</m> acts on <m>w\in W</m> by the following way:
				<me>(a,w)\mapsto a\unit_V(w)=a\cdot w\in W,</me>
				where <m>a\cdot w</m> is the scalar multiplication via the vector space structure. For any <m>w\in W</m> we have <m>(X,w)\mapsto T(w)\in W</m> and hence <m>W</m> is a <m>T</m>-invariant subspace of <m>V</m>.
			</p>
			<p>
				Conversely assume that <m>W</m> is a <m>T</m>-invariant subspace of <m>V</m>. Then for any <m>n\in\N</m> and any <m>a_n\in F</m> we have <m>W</m> is <m>a_nT^n</m>-invariant subspace of <m>V</m>. Therefore, for any <m>w\in W</m> and any <m>a_0+a_X+\cdots+a_nX^n\in F[X]</m>, we get that 
				<me>\left(a_0+a_1X+\cdots+a_nT^n,w\right)\mapsto a_0\unit_V(w)+a_1T(w)+\cdots+a_nT^n(w)\in W</me>
				Hence <m>W</m> is an <m>F[X]</m>-submodule.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</example>
	<definition xml:id="def-proper-nontrivial-submodule">
		<title>(Proper submodule and non-trivial submodule)</title>
		A left <m>R</m>-submodule <m>N\leq M</m> is said to be <term>proper</term> if <m>N\neq M</m> and <m>N</m> is said to be <term>non-trivial</term> if <m>N\neq\{0\}</m>.
	</definition>
	<definition xml:id="def-simple-module">
		<title>(Simple module)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>R</m> be a ring and let <m>M</m> be an <m>R</m>-module. We say that <m>M</m> is <term>simple module</term> if <m>M</m> has no proper non-trivial submodule.
		</statement>
	</definition>
	<lemma xml:id="simple-implies-cyclic">
		<statement>
			If <m>M</m> is a simple left <m>R</m>-module then it is a cyclic module.
		</statement>
	</lemma>
	<proof>
		Let <m>0\neq m\in M</m>. Consider the left non-trivial submodule generated by <m>m</m>, <m>Rm</m>. Since <m>M</m> is simple and <m>Rm\neq \{0\}</m> we have <m>M=Rm</m>.
	</proof>
	<example xml:id="simple-abelian-groups">
		<title>(Simple abelian groups)</title>
		<statement>
			In <xref ref="abelian-groups-Z-modules"/> we showed that <m>\Z</m>-modules are precisely abelian groups. Thus a simple <m>\Z</m>-module must be a cyclic group of a prime order.
		</statement>
	</example>
	<example xml:id="simple-modules-of-End">
		<title>(Vector space as an <m>\End_F(V)</m>-module is simple)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field <m>F</m>. As in <xref ref="vs-as-End-module"/> we consider <m>V</m> as an <m>\End_F(V)</m>-module. We show that <m>V</m> is a simple <m>\End_F(V)</m>-module.
			<p>
				In view of <xref ref="simple-implies-cyclic"/> it is enough to show that given any <m>v,w\in V</m> with <m>v\neq 0</m> there exists <m>T\in\End_F(V)</m> such that <m>T(v)=w</m>. Since <m>v\neq 0</m> we can extend <m>\{v\}</m> to a basis of <m>V</m>, say <m>\{v,v_1,\ldots,v_{n-1}\}</m>. For a set <m>\{w,w_1,\ldots,w_{n-1}\}\subset V</m> we define a map <m>T(v)=w</m> and <m>T(v_i)=w_i</m>, and we extend <m>T</m> linearly. Thus <m>T\in\End_F(V)</m> is a required map.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</example>
</section>